Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — singleton: one HttpClient/connection pool shared app-wide
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient: fresh state each time a page is navigated to
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient: new instance per navigation (pairs with its ViewModel)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`/REST calls. One instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you cache auth tokens or headers in one place. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should start with clean state (no stale data from a previous visit). |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the ViewModel lifetime—each navigation gets a fresh page + fresh ViewModel injected via constructor. |

> **When to use Scoped instead:** If you adopt Shell-based navigation with `Routing.RegisterRoute` and want a ViewModel to survive _within_ a navigation scope but not globally, register it as `AddScoped`. In MAUI, scoped ≈ per-navigation-scope, but transient is the safer default.
